result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The defendant shall not commit any criminal offenses; shall notify the Taylor County District Attorney's Office, as well as the Clerk of Court's office, of any change of address within ten days of said change.  Within six months of entering agreement the defendant shall attend and complete counseling with a provider of defendant's choice.  Proof of counseling must be provided to the District Attorney's Office within said six month period.  Defendant shall write a letter of apology to the victim due before the plea hearing.

judgments.dispoDesc: Pursuant to an agreement and on motion of the State, the court granted a deferred entry of judgment for a period of one year.  Upon successful completion of the agreement, the State will move to dismiss the charge

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Kathryn L. Retzlaff

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Kathryn L. Retzlaff in court with attorney Alec Phillip Nocco.  Kristi S. Tlusty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Plea agreement put into the record.  Victim rights have been complied with.  Plea of no contest to count 2 disorderly conduct - domestic.  Plea colloquy.  Plea freely, voluntarily and intelligently; factual basis exists.  Court dismisses and read in count 1.  Court finds defendant guilty of count 2 and defers entry of judgment for one year with conditions of no new criminal charges; submit a letter of apology to victim; attend and complete counseling with a provider of defendant's choice.  Upon successful completion of the deferred entry of judgment the State agrees to dismiss the charge.   Court signs agreement. - rt
Order for Appearance at Settlement Conference; Report to Court on Results of Settlement Conference.

Defendant Kathryn L. Retzlaff nka as Kathryn Behnke in court with attorney Alec Phillip Nocco.  Kristi S. Tlusty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Nocco waives reading of complaint and enters plea of not guilty to all charges.  Bond continued.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for October 19, 2015 at 02:45 pm.  - rt
Defendant shall not leave the State of Wisconsin without prior notice to and written approval of the court. Defendant shall comply with booking procedures at the Taylor County Sheriff's Department.
Initial Appearance on September 22, 2015 at 2:00 p.m.

Kristi Tlusty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Kathryn L. Retzlaff appeared in person, in custody.  Attorney Tlusty requests a $500.00 signature bond and booking.  Court questions defendant.  Court orders a $500.00 signature bond with booking.  Court advises defendant of right to an attorney.  Next court date is September 22, 2015 at 2:00 p.m.  - rt
